For inorganic semiconductors, the coherent wavelength of thermally activated electrons or holes at room temperature is close to the acoustic photon wavelength and is much larger than their lattice constant. The scattering of the thermal electron or hole can be dominated by the electron–acoustic phonon coupling at low-energy regime,48,56–58 which can be calculated by the DP theory proposed by Bardeen and Shockley.18 On the basis of effective mass approximation, the carrier mobility (µ) for 3D materials can be expressed as1μ3D=22πeℏ4C3D3(κBT)3/2m∗5/2E12,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
